  "chunk_index": 13,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot visits the Rundell household, where he meets Dr. Rundell and his wife, Hilda. During the visit, Poirot observes that Mrs. Rundell is a timid woman who appears to obey her husband blindly. He notes that the deceased housekeeper, Mrs. McGinty, used to work at this residence on Tuesday mornings.\n\nPoirot then travels to Hunter's Manor, a large Victorian building. He is met by a foreign girl and led to meet Miss Dillie Henderson, the plain and wary thirty-year-old stepdaughter of Mr. Wetherby. Poirot explains that he is conducting an investigation on behalf of James Bentley's defense lawyer to gather new evidence regarding Mrs. McGinty's cause of death. Miss Henderson expresses a dislike for Mrs. McGinty, describing her as a good worker who talked too much.\n\nDillie leads Poirot upstairs to a cluttered room filled with travel souvenirs to meet her mother, Mrs. Wetherby. Mrs. Wetherby appears delicate and claims to be resting on doctor's orders. When questioned about Mrs. McGinty, Mrs. Wetherby expresses distress, recalling that the woman was \"stupid\" for keeping money under the floor instead of in a bank. She mentions that Mrs. McGinty had a \"dreadful\" and well-educated lodger. Mrs. Wetherby also speculates that the murder weapon, a carving knife, was thrown into a pond. Dillie interrupts the conversation, fiercely telling Poirot to stop questioning her mother due to her sensitivity. Poirot concludes the meeting by stating his motive: he is investigating because someone is scheduled to be hanged in three weeks, and he must determine if the accused is truly responsible.",
